note as RelationshipCorrections
  <b>Relationship cardinalities corrected by LLM review</b>
  AuditEntry "1" -- "1" REQ_FRAUD_01 → AuditEntry "*" -- "1" REQ_FRAUD_01
    Reason: Multiple audit entries can belong to one fraud requirement, not a one-to-one association. Many suspicious transactions can be linked to the same fraud detection rule.
  REQ_FRAUD_01 "1" -- "*" Interface → REQ_FRAUD_01 "1" -- "1" Interface
    Reason: A fraud detection requirement typically involves a single interface (the fraud detection system), not many. The multiplicity should be 1 for the interface.
  User "1" *-- "1" Card → User "1" o-- "1" Card
    Reason: A user owns a card via composition, but the cardinality should be one-to-one (each user has one card, each card belongs to one user). The arrow should be 'o--' (aggregation) since the card can exist without the user, but *-- implies many users share one card, which is incorrect.
  User "1" *-- "1" PIN → User "1" o-- "1" PIN
    Reason: Similarly, a user has one PIN, and a PIN belongs to one user. Use aggregation (o--) rather than composition with reversed multiplicity.
end note

note as ArchitectureCorrections
  <b>Architecture mistakes corrected automatically</b>
  [wrong_inheritance] User inherits from Resource via association arrow --|>, but Resource represents a generic concept and User should be a specific Actor, not a Resource.
    Fix applied: change_class_type
  [wrong_class_type] FinancialDatabase is an interface but is used as a concrete class in composition with Account.
    Fix applied: change_class_type
  [duplicate_concept] AuditEntry, AuditLog, AuditLogEntry likely represent the same concept; tasks #87 and #84 refer to audit logs.
    Fix applied: merge_classes
  [missing_relationship] Account should have a composition or aggregation relationship with Card and PIN to reflect card-and-PIN authentication.
    Fix applied: add_relation
end note

